member.name: T:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile
member.summary: The base class for section profiles which are non-composite - i.e. formed of a single material.
member.remarks: DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile Class implementation.

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.GetPerimeter
member.summary: Get the outer perimeter of this section as a closed collection of curves. Perimeter will be drawn in the X-Y plane with it's origin at the mid-x and mid-y point of the section. For a perimeter set-out according to the section's Offset, HorizontalSetOut and VerticalSetOut options, use the GetSetOutPerimeter function instead. Curves run in an anti-clockwise direction.

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.GetSetOutPerimeter(DesignLink.Types.CurveCollectionCollection@)
member.summary: Get the outer (and, if applicable, inner) perimeter curves of this section, set-out according to the Offset, HorizontalSetOut and VerticalSetOut settings of this section and drawn in the X-Y plane. All curves run in an anti-clockwise direction.
member.param: OUTPUT: The collection of void curves inside this section.

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.CalculateSectionCentroid(DesignLink.Types.CurveCollection,DesignLink.Types.CurveCollectionCollection)
member.summary: Internal function to return the centroid of this section given its perimeter and voids. As an optimisation, section types which are symmetrical in both axes (and where the centroid thus coincides with the mid-point) can override this function to return a 0,0 point without the need to carry out any calculations.

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.GetVoids
member.summary: Get the perimeter of any inner voids in this section as a collection of closed curve collections. The perimeter(s) will be drawn in the X-Y plane with it's origin at the mid-x and mid-y point of the section. For a set of void curves set-out according to the section's Offset, HorizontalSetOut and VerticalSetOut options, use the GetSetOutPerimeter function instead. Curves run in an anti-clockwise direction.

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.ToArbitrarySectionProfile
member.summary: Convert this section profile to an ArbitrarySectionProfile with its geometry defined by a closed set of perimeter and void curves. Applicable properties from this section will be copied into the new one.
member.returns: A new ArbitrarySectionProfile with it's geometry defined to match this one

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.CalculateAreaCentroid(System.Double@)
member.summary: Calculate the area centroid of this section profile (and incidentally, its cross-sectional area). The centroid is described relative to the mid-X and mid-Y point of the section.
member.returns: A Point3d object describing the centroid of this section relative to it's mid-X and mid-Y point

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.CalculateGeometricProperties
member.summary: Calculate a set of geometric properties for this section. This is a work in progress - not all properties can currently be calculated for all sections. Reinforcement is ignored and the material is assumed to be linear-elastic. Currently supported geometric properties are: Area, A for all sections. Second moments of area Ixx and Iyy for all sections. Torsion constant J for standard section types (not arbitrary ones).

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.CalculateTorsionConstant
member.summary: Calculate the torsional constant J for this section. May only be approximate - fillets, lips etc. will be excluded. Note that this is implemented only for standard section types at present.

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.RectangleJ(System.Double,System.Double)
member.summary: Static helper function to calculate the contribution to the torsion constant J of an open section from a rectangle. Includes calculation of the K scaling factor which varies depending on the ratio of the maximum to minimum dimension of the rectangle.

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.SimpleSectionProfile.TaperJ(System.Double,System.Double,System.Double)
member.summary: Static helper function to calculate the contribution to the torsion constant J of an open section from a trapezoid. Uses Roark's formula. Only accurate when the ratio of length to thickness is > 3.

member.summary: A prestress applied along the axis of a beam object. This can be an InitialPrestress Force which will change as the structure deforms, an initial strain, a lack of fit (axial displacement of an end node of the structure), or a ConstantPrestressForce which simulates a prestressing tendon inside the member that is much less stiff than the member it is prestressing

member.name: P:DesignLink.Types.StructBeamPrestress.OffsetFromCentroid
member.summary: The offset of the Initial or Constant Prestress Force which will create a bending moment in the member. Stored as a Vector3d from the centroid to the location of the force. Z assumed to be 0, X and Y axes align with Beam profile axes (i.e X = -Y element axis, and Y = Z element axis)
member.remarks: Sets or gets the value of the object class.

member.name: P:DesignLink.Types.StructBeamPrestress.Value
member.summary: The value of the prestress applied to the Beam. A positive pre-stress force is equivalent to a negative Initial Strain or negaitve lack of Fit, and will result in a tension in the element for normal structures. Where the prestress type is a force this value represents the force applied. Where it is an intial strain this is the value of strain applied and where it is an initial lack of fit this value represents the change in length in distance units.
member.remarks: Sets or gets the value of the object class.

member.name: M:DesignLink.Types.Tools.CreateCompressedGUID
member.summary: Creates a Base 64 GUID string, which is an IFC GUID, prefixed with DL-
member.returns: A string, in Base64 encoding which can be used to create an IFC compatible GUID
member.remarks:
For XML compatibility reasons, the 22 character, base 64 IFC compatibile GUID is prefixed with the letters "DL-" so as to ensure the GUID is also a valid XML ID value.
"DL-" was chosen XML ID values must start with a letter, cannot contain : but can contain - which the IFC GUID won't, so DL- will be a prefix that is XML compliant but shouldn't appear as part of a normal IFC compressed guid.
Note: This function uses a Guid Factory, which can be overridden

member.summary: A property that can be used to hold transient application-specific data of any object type. This can be used to temporarily 'tag' designLink objects with custom additional information. Objects stored in this way will not (currently) be serialised when this object is and will not persist between sessions. member.name: T:DesignLink.Types.EnergyAnalysis2DElement
member.summary: WORK IN PROGRESS! A typical 'plate model' element forming part of a Energy Analysis member representation.. This representation is designed to handle Walls that are cut with Windows, where the wall is the overall bounding area and windows are polygons within it. This maps well to the 'Energy+' style of representing a Wall and Window. The Radiance writer is exploiting the fact that Radiance doesn't mind having a complex perimeter that includes both the wall and the window polygons as one preimeter, even if some of the edges are co-incident, or run over internal edges. IFC analog: ???

member.name: P:DesignLink.Types.EnergyAnalysis2DElement.CuttingElements
member.summary: A list of EnergyAnalysis2dElements which cut through the parent element to create windows, voids etc. It is the users responsibility to ensure that these cuting elements are non-overlapping, sensible shapes that do not cross the Perimeter of the profile. They shold all be of the type EnergyAnalysi2dElement where the 'ElementType' property is set to 'Void' or 'Window'. Where an EnergyAnalysis2dElement is a child (i.e part of a CuttingElements collection) then the use of 'CuttingElements' within the child is not allowed, (i.e 1 level deep only)

member.name: T:DesignLink.Types.VariableThicknessFaceProperty
member.summary: This class describes the properties for a panel like element of variable thickness, e.g. for analyzing a tapered shell. The panel thickness is defined at each corner node - (3 values for a TRI, 4 values for a QUAD element). For triangular elements N4Thickness is not needed: typical practice is to set this value to match N3Thickness, but this is not necessary. The order of the thicknesses corresponds to the node ordering defined at the element level (counterclockwise).

member.name: T:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType
member.summary: The different types of elements that can be analyzed based on the behaviour of the element, what deformations are incuded in the analysis, and what types of load (eg tension only for fabric) can be carried by the element
member.remarks: DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType enumeration.

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.PlaneStress
member.summary: The element only experiences stress in the plane of the element and has 2 degrees of freedom at each note dx,dy

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.PlaneStrain
member.summary: The element only experiences deformation (strain) in the plane of the element and has 2 degrees of freedom at each note dx,dy

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.Shear
member.summary: The element only has shear stiffness in the plane of the element

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.Axisymmetric
member.summary: The element only experiences in plane effects (the out of plane direction is the hoop direction of a rotationally symmetric object)

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.Membrane
member.summary: The element only experiences membrane deformation and has 3 degrees of freedom at each note dx,dy,dz as opposed to plane stress and plane strain elements that have 2 DOF per node

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.Fabric
member.summary: The element only experiences membrane deformation and cannot carry compressive membrane forces

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.ThinPlateBending
member.summary: The element only experiences bending (out of plane) deformation, neglecting membrane effects and neglecting through thickness shear

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.ThickPlateBending
member.summary: The element only experiences bending (out of plane) deformation and through thickness shear, neglecting membrane effects

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.ThinShell
member.summary: The element experiences in (membrane) and out of plane (bending) effects but neglects through thickness shear

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.ThickShell
member.summary: The element experiences in (membrane) and out of plane (bending) effects and through thickness shear

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.Wall
member.summary: The element represents a wall

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.Load
member.summary: The element represents a load panel

member.name: F:DesignLink.Types.Struct2dElementDeformationType.Unknown
member.summary: A 2D element deformation type that is not defined

member.name: P:DesignLink.Types.StructAnalysis2DElement.Nodes
member.summary: The list of nodes, in anti-clockwise order describing this planar Analysis element. Note: It is the users responsibility to add the correct amount of StructNodes to the collection, i.e either 3,4,6, 8, or 9 and in the correct order. The ''''''ElementType'''''' property returns it''''''s answer based on the number of nodes in the collection. Note: For Tri6 and Quad8 type elements, the primary vertex nodes are all added first in anti-clockwise order, then the ''''''secondary'''''' nodes that lie along the edges also in anti-clockwise order. This is inline with GSA and Strand7 The edges of Tri6,Quad8 and Quad9 are quadratic curves fit through the 3 nodes that define an element edge

member.name: P:DesignLink.Types.StructAnalysisCase.LoadCombination
member.summary: The collection of factored loads to be applied during this analysis case. These loads will be factored and combined before the analysis is run, allowing for non-linear analysis to be performed. Where only a linear analysis is required and the design contains no tension-only or compression-only elements it may be preferable (faster) to use a ResultCombination to factor and combine the post-analysis results instead.

member.summary: The value of the prestress applied to the element in the local x-direction. member.name: T:DesignLink.Types.CurveCollection
member.summary: A collection of Curve like objects, useful for creating closed shapes. If used as an ordered collection of edges,it is the users responsibility to ensure that items are put into the collection in the correct order, with the end point of one edge corresponding with the start point of the next edge. It is also the users responsibility to ensure the curves/edges are planar, and generally in the same plane. If a closed shape is required, it's the users responsibility to ensure the endpoint of the last curve matches the startpoint of the first curve.
member.remarks: Type-safe collection class for an array of objects.
